to the Judeo-Christian belief

564
00:23:39,635 --> 00:23:41,288
in an all-knowing Creator

565
00:23:41,332 --> 00:23:44,900
while denying the soul's
potential for life everlasting.

566
00:23:45,989 --> 00:23:47,512
Shut up.

567
00:23:50,820 --> 00:23:52,255
How'd you get the hernia?

568
00:23:52,300 --> 00:23:54,344
-I don't know.
-You don't know?

569
00:23:54,389 --> 00:23:56,782
Could've been anything--
soccer, hockey.

570
00:23:56,826 --> 00:23:58,392
They didn't know for sure.

571
00:23:58,437 --> 00:24:00,916
[Paul] How did they find out?

572
00:24:00,961 --> 00:24:02,440
What do you mean
"How'd they find out?"

573
00:24:02,484 --> 00:24:04,137
How did you know
that you had a hernia?

574
00:24:04,181 --> 00:24:06,139
During the physical, when
the doctor grabbed my balls

575
00:24:06,183 --> 00:24:07,923
and told me to cough.

576
00:24:07,968 --> 00:24:09,577
Didn't they ever do that
to you?

577
00:24:09,622 --> 00:24:10,926
Yeah.

578
00:24:10,971 --> 00:24:12,798
Well, didn't you know
what that was for?

579
00:24:12,842 --> 00:24:14,626
No.

580
00:24:14,670 --> 00:24:17,193
I mean, I think now, I--

581
00:24:17,238 --> 00:24:20,153
So you just let some guy grab
your balls without knowing why?

582
00:24:20,197 --> 00:24:22,111
-Well, he was a doctor.
-So what?

583
00:24:22,156 --> 00:24:23,461
You didn't ask him
what he was doing that for?

584
00:24:23,505 --> 00:24:25,985
-I was 10.
-You shoulda asked!

585
00:24:26,029 --> 00:24:27,552
You shoulda said,
"What the fuck are you doing?"

586
00:24:27,596 --> 00:24:29,292
I was 10!

587
00:24:30,817 --> 00:24:34,646
♪

588
00:24:34,690 --> 00:24:37,039
You're not supposed
to be here, dude!

589
00:24:37,084 --> 00:24:39,259
-I just came to see--
-Take off, Tiger Beat.

590
00:24:39,303 --> 00:24:42,349
♪

591
00:24:47,355 --> 00:24:49,530
Who was that?

592
00:24:49,575 --> 00:24:51,489
It was the ghost
of Ritchie Valens.

593
00:24:51,533 --> 00:24:53,142
How do I know who it was?

594
00:24:53,187 --> 00:24:56,319
♪

595
00:24:56,364 --> 00:24:59,192
So, what other things
do you let doctors do to you

596
00:24:59,236 --> 00:25:01,324
that you didn't know
why they were doing them?

597
00:25:02,283 --> 00:25:04,110
[chuckles]

598
00:25:04,154 --> 00:25:05,459
[interviewer]
There's a candlelight vigil.

599
00:25:05,504 --> 00:25:06,939
Are you gonna go to that?

600
00:25:06,983 --> 00:25:08,984
I didn't get invited.

601
00:25:09,029 --> 00:25:10,508
-Everyone's going.
-[interviewer] Really?

602
00:25:10,552 --> 00:25:12,074
There's, like, hundreds
of people going.

603
00:25:12,119 --> 00:25:13,685
-Hundreds.
-Hundreds, probably.

604
00:25:13,729 --> 00:25:15,382
-[interviewer] Really?
-Yeah, I mean--

605
00:25:15,426 --> 00:25:18,385
-A thousand people are going.
-Thousands, I think.

606
00:25:18,429 --> 00:25:20,474
We're all coming
from different cities.

607
00:25:20,519 --> 00:25:21,823
We're gonna go,
and we're gonna, like,

608
00:25:21,868 --> 00:25:23,390
have our own outfits,
and we're just gonna

609
00:25:23,434 --> 00:25:24,913
set everything out
and just, like, camp out there.

610
00:25:24,958 --> 00:25:26,436
-We're camping out there.
-[interviewer] Right.

611
00:25:26,481 --> 00:25:28,438
We want to be next to him.

612
00:25:28,483 --> 00:25:30,136
Pandemonium.

613
00:25:30,180 --> 00:25:32,442
[crowd cheering, man howling]

614
00:25:32,487 --> 00:25:36,446
♪

615
00:25:36,491 --> 00:25:38,057
[snoring]

616
00:25:38,101 --> 00:25:39,841
[man in headphones]
...the changing of the guard

617
00:25:39,886 --> 00:25:43,018
as the neon throbs in purple,
timed to the music.

618
00:25:43,063 --> 00:25:45,673
[dog barking]

619
00:25:47,633 --> 00:25:49,851
[owl hooting]

620
00:25:51,680 --> 00:25:53,463
[snoring continues]

621
00:25:53,508 --> 00:25:54,987
You're not supposed
to be here, man.

622
00:25:55,031 --> 00:25:57,119
Um, my name's Dean.
I--I just came to look.

623
00:25:57,164 --> 00:26:00,296
Yeah? Well, well, there's
nothing to see, Dean.

624
00:26:00,341 --> 00:26:02,647
Hey, what happened to him?

625
00:26:02,691 --> 00:26:05,345
[snoring]

626
00:26:05,389 --> 00:26:07,869
Nothing. Really--
you're not supposed to be here.

627
00:26:07,914 --> 00:26:10,263
All right, that's cool.
I'm going.

628
00:26:10,307 --> 00:26:12,395
Hey, it's pretty awesome, huh?

629
00:26:12,440 --> 00:26:14,397
-What is?
-Um, you know, getting to be

630
00:26:14,442 --> 00:26:16,965
so close to Colin all night
and everything.

631
00:26:17,706 --> 00:26:19,446
[Paul] Not really.
I didn't really know him.

632
00:26:19,490 --> 00:26:22,144
Oh, oh, man,
he--he was like, um,

633
00:26:22,189 --> 00:26:24,407
well, you know...

634
00:26:24,452 --> 00:26:26,279
-I met him once.
-Oh, yeah?

635
00:26:26,323 --> 00:26:27,976
Yeah, he'd just gotten
offstage, and I said to him,

636
00:26:28,021 --> 00:26:29,717
I said to him, I said,
"Party time," you know?

637
00:26:29,762 --> 00:26:33,112
Because that's one of his songs,
you know, "Party Time."

638
00:26:33,156 --> 00:26:34,853
Well, I guess that wasn't the
right time to say "party time,"

639
00:26:34,897 --> 00:26:36,376
you know, because
he'd gotten just offstage,

640
00:26:36,420 --> 00:26:38,204
and that's more downtime
than anything,

641
00:26:38,248 --> 00:26:40,423
not party time,
so he kicked me.

642
00:26:40,468 --> 00:26:42,295
-He kicked you?
-Oh, not hard, you know,

643
00:26:42,339 --> 00:26:43,818
just in the side of my face,
you know?

644
00:26:43,863 --> 00:26:45,733
I--I deserved it.

645
00:26:45,778 --> 00:26:46,952
I shouldn't have said
"party time."

646
00:26:46,996 --> 00:26:49,171
It was so stupid!

647
00:26:49,216 --> 00:26:52,653
You know, I shoulda said
something like, um,

648
00:26:52,698 --> 00:26:55,743
"Good show, man," you know,
or something like that.

649
00:26:55,788 --> 00:26:57,963
-Maybe.
-Yeah.

650
00:26:58,007 --> 00:27:00,095
I guess that's why I came,
you know?

651
00:27:01,228 --> 00:27:04,143
Just so I could say
"Good show, man."

652
00:27:04,187 --> 00:27:06,536
-Is that cool?
-Okay.

653
00:27:06,581 --> 00:27:08,626
But just--well--

654
00:27:08,670 --> 00:27:10,410
do it from here.

655
00:27:12,065 --> 00:27:13,631
Good show, man.

656
00:27:13,675 --> 00:27:15,502
[snoring]

657
00:27:17,287 --> 00:27:18,636
God.

658
00:27:20,856 --> 00:27:22,378
Okay.

659
00:27:22,423 --> 00:27:24,511
This is his story

660
00:27:24,555 --> 00:27:26,469
told in comic-book form.

661
00:27:27,558 --> 00:27:29,168
Okay, now, this--
this is how he learned

662
00:27:29,212 --> 00:27:30,822
to play the guitar
when he was only three.

663
00:27:30,866 --> 00:27:33,259
His aunt had one made
for his tiny, little hands.

664
00:27:33,303 --> 00:27:35,827
Oh, wow.
This--this here,

665
00:27:35,871 --> 00:27:39,134
this is his first concert.

666
00:27:39,179 --> 00:27:41,484
He got booed because he wore
this T-shirt, right, that said

667
00:27:41,529 --> 00:27:43,530
"Stop harvesting the ocean,"

668
00:27:43,574 --> 00:27:45,184
you know, which was a mistake
in New Bedford, right,

669
00:27:45,228 --> 00:27:46,576
so these two guys,
they came up onstage,

670
00:27:46,621 --> 00:27:48,753
and they threw him
into the crowd!

671
00:27:48,797 --> 00:27:50,450
You know.
Now, fortunately for him,

672
00:27:50,494 --> 00:27:52,191
though, he--
he lands on this guy, right,

673
00:27:52,235 --> 00:27:53,845
from this big record company,
right?

674
00:27:53,889 --> 00:27:55,194
He liked Colin
right off the bat.

675
00:27:55,238 --> 00:27:58,588
He signs him
to a three-record deal.

676
00:27:59,547 --> 00:28:02,636
Then...he went to Sweden.

677
00:28:04,073 --> 00:28:06,379
He's wicked big in Sweden.

678
00:28:06,423 --> 00:28:09,774
Every household in Sweden
has a copy of his first album.

679
00:28:09,818 --> 00:28:12,820
Do you know what the number-one
name for boys in Sweden is?

680
00:28:12,865 --> 00:28:14,039
It's Colin.

681
00:28:14,083 --> 00:28:15,910
Wait.

682
00:28:15,955 --> 00:28:17,303
What about Sweden?

683
00:28:17,347 --> 00:28:19,000
They really like him.

684
00:28:19,045 --> 00:28:20,915
-[imitates drums]
-[rock music enters]

685
00:28:20,960 --> 00:28:23,178
-What the fuck are you doing?
-Hey, man, don't ruin my book.

686
00:28:23,223 --> 00:28:25,703
-Ow, ow, ow, ow!
-Hey, don't hurt him.

687
00:28:25,747 --> 00:28:27,269
[Grady] Get outta here!

688
00:28:27,314 --> 00:28:30,359
♪

689
00:28:32,972 --> 00:28:35,234
Should we kill him?

690
00:28:35,278 --> 00:28:37,366
[interviewer] Have you been
to his grave since he died?

691
00:28:37,411 --> 00:28:38,716
Yeah.

692
00:28:38,760 --> 00:28:41,762
It was kind of cathartic, but--

693
00:28:41,807 --> 00:28:43,242
[interviewer] Why is that?

694
00:28:43,286 --> 00:28:45,723
Uh, 'cause I felt an emotion.

695
00:28:45,767 --> 00:28:48,464
[owl hooting]

696
00:28:48,509 --> 00:28:51,250
[crunching]

697
00:28:56,125 --> 00:28:57,691
Sorry about your cat.

698
00:28:57,736 --> 00:28:59,127
What cat?

699
00:29:00,608 --> 00:29:03,566
-The one you're looking for.
-I'm not looking for a cat.

700
00:29:03,611 --> 00:29:05,220
What about the flyer
you put up?

701
00:29:05,265 --> 00:29:07,396
Oh!
Did you like that?

702
00:29:07,441 --> 00:29:10,095
-Did I like what?
-[Grady] What'd you think?

703
00:29:10,139 --> 00:29:12,662
I don't understand.
You lost a cat?

704
00:29:12,707 --> 00:29:14,795
I hate cats.
I made that shit up.

705
00:29:14,840 --> 00:29:16,536
You don't have a cat?

706
00:29:16,580 --> 00:29:17,798
[Grady] No.

707
00:29:18,713 --> 00:29:21,410
You invent lost animals?

708
00:29:21,455 --> 00:29:23,369
Yeah.
Why?

709
00:29:23,413 --> 00:29:24,762
Gro--that's sick.

710
00:29:24,806 --> 00:29:26,328
Why would you do that?

711
00:29:26,373 --> 00:29:28,591
-I don't know.
-[Paul] That's stupid!

712
00:29:28,636 --> 00:29:30,637
How's it any different
than what he did?

713
00:29:31,987 --> 00:29:35,120
Wait, wait, you--

714
00:29:35,164 --> 00:29:38,210
you're not comparing yourself
to Colin Fitz, are you?

715
00:29:38,254 --> 00:29:42,214
I mean, that's just ridiculous!

716
00:29:42,258 --> 00:29:45,304
Come on!
He was an artist!

717
00:29:45,348 --> 00:29:47,132
I give people
something to look for.

718
00:29:47,176 --> 00:29:49,134
-Imaginary animals?
-Whatever.

719
00:29:49,178 --> 00:29:51,179
That's something.
And who knows?

720
00:29:51,224 --> 00:29:53,965
Maybe while they're looking for
the little kitten or the bunny,

721
00:29:54,009 --> 00:29:57,055
they find something else,
like...

722
00:29:57,099 --> 00:29:59,448
-Themselves?
-What do you mean?

723
00:29:59,493 --> 00:30:02,495
[laughing]
You are no Colin Fitz.

724
00:30:02,539 --> 00:30:05,019
-[Grady] He sucked!
-He changed lives!

725
00:30:05,064 --> 00:30:08,718
Rock music is just music.

726
00:30:08,763 --> 00:30:11,809
It's not something to get your
panties all bunched up over.

727
00:30:11,853 --> 00:30:13,593
In the history of rock music,

728
00:30:13,637 --> 00:30:17,292
there's only been one major
result of a particular song.

729
00:30:17,337 --> 00:30:19,642
Neil Young's "Keep On Rockin'
in the Free World"

730
00:30:19,687 --> 00:30:22,732
was responsible
for the collapse of communism.

731
00:30:22,777 --> 00:30:24,865
Everything else,
it's just driving music.

732
00:30:24,910 --> 00:30:29,261
Neil Young was responsible
for the fall of communism?

733
00:30:29,305 --> 00:30:30,871
Yeah, 1989.

734
00:30:30,916 --> 00:30:32,655
That song got over
the Berlin Wall.

735
00:30:32,700 --> 00:30:34,440
There was no taking it back.

736
00:30:34,484 --> 00:30:37,312
What about Woodstock, Live Aid?

737
00:30:37,357 --> 00:30:39,314
All of that had no impact?

738
00:30:39,359 --> 00:30:41,316
[Grady] On record sales, sure.

739
00:30:41,361 --> 00:30:45,233
But do you think that, to this
day, the people of Ethiopia

740
00:30:45,278 --> 00:30:48,628
are saying,
"Thank God for Bananarama"?

741
00:30:48,672 --> 00:30:51,587
Are there Haircut
One Hundred statues?

742
00:30:51,632 --> 00:30:52,850
I don't think so.

743
00:30:52,894 --> 00:30:54,808
But they made
young people aware

744
00:30:54,853 --> 00:30:57,506
-of the problems in the world.
-So?

745
00:30:57,551 --> 00:30:59,944
I'm aware that people
are starving.

746
00:30:59,988 --> 00:31:02,424
I'm aware that people
are killing other people.

747
00:31:02,469 --> 00:31:04,209
I'm aware that people
are selling cigarettes

748
00:31:04,253 --> 00:31:05,340
to underage minors.

749
00:31:05,385 --> 00:31:07,342
And what am I doing, huh?

750
00:31:07,387 --> 00:31:09,431
That's up to you!

751
00:31:11,608 --> 00:31:14,523
-Give me your keys.
-What?

752
00:31:14,568 --> 00:31:16,438
Give me your keys.
I gotta go do something.

753
00:31:16,483 --> 00:31:19,398
What are you gonna do?
Feed people?

754
00:31:19,442 --> 00:31:21,574
Just give me your keys.
I'll be right back.

755
00:31:21,618 --> 00:31:23,532
What if Mr. O'Day shows up?

756
00:31:23,577 --> 00:31:25,230
Tell him I chased someone away.

757
00:31:25,274 --> 00:31:27,493
And how far were you planning
on chasing this person?

758
00:31:27,537 --> 00:31:29,669
Until I catch 'em.
Give me your keys.

759
00:31:29,713 --> 00:31:32,672
[rock music]

760
00:31:32,716 --> 00:31:34,108
[keys jangle]

761
00:31:43,336 --> 00:31:47,600
[Colin] ♪ I've got to find
Some peace of mind ♪

762
00:31:49,124 --> 00:31:54,215
♪ Teach me how to release
My time ♪

763
00:31:54,260 --> 00:31:58,132
♪ I've got to get
My piece of cake ♪

764
00:31:59,743 --> 00:32:03,790
